node.text:
Sharon Quirk-Silva was interviewed outside of Disneyland today. She shared her thoughts about the Governors decision not to allow theme parks such as Disneyland to reopen until the county has reached the yellow tier. I wasn’t sure if my iPhone was picking up what she was saying so I tried to ensure I reiterated most of what she was saying. Disneyland is pushing hard to reopen. It’ll be interesting to see what happens as this is the first time in Disneyland history that the park has been shut down for such an extensive period of time.

node.text:
This is totally outside of the typical content I create and post, but I felt so strongly that this specific scene in the Netflix documentary Schitts Creek Best Wishes, Warmest Regards needed to be shared. Forgive me, you can hear me sniffling and crying as I filmed this. Schitts Creek is one of my favorite shows and has served as a super catalyst for acceptance, love, and positive personification of the LGBTQ+ community. I share some of my own thoughts and feelings (not very eloquently bc I had a hard time NOT crying) after the scene. I absolutely love that I am seeing more and more support LGBTQ+ community, but I also experience a devastating amount of hate on a daily basis. My goal behind our social media has been and will continue to be to offer ppl a small glimpse into our lives as a family in the hopes that we might open a few minds and hearts along the way. Love is love ❤️ And I hope and pray we see more and more queer representation in movies, television shows, books, etc. 🏳️‍🌈✊🏽 @schittscreek @instadanjlevy @annefrances 
.
.

node.text:
We have so many wonderful new followers I thought it would be a good idea to re-introduce our fam!

My name is Eeka and I’m the matriarch of the family 👋🏽 I’m a single adoptive mama & an ex-foster mom. I fostered 18 children in the time I was a licensed home. I have 2 Masters Degrees, am asexual & biromantic, a living kidney donor, Disney enthusiast, and a grandma at only 40 years old. I love mimosas, eating out, and dancing.

Eli is 7 and was the first to make me a mommy. Eli has sever cerebral palsy, short gut syndrome, fetal alcohol, and vision impairment. I received the call for him when he was 4 months old and legally adopted him when he was 1 1/2 years old. Eli LOVES expensive food, toy cars, and the movie Frozen. He is 100% Chinese and my easiest most laid back kiddo by far!

Evan is 5 (6 in a few weeks) and was my next adoption. Evan was 5 days old when he was placed with me and 13 months old when I legally adopted him. Evan has been diagnosed with microcephaly and autism. He’s very smart and incredibly creative. Evan began wearing dresses when he was 3 years old and has continued to be the fanciest queen I’ve ever met! Evan loves anything and everything Disney, French fries, and making TikTok videos.

Emaya is 20 and was placed in our home when she was 15 and 1 month pregnant. I never formally adopted her and will be looking into adult adoptions ASAP! Emaya has experienced incredible trauma in her life and in her own words is “still recovering” from her past. Emaya has a 4 year old son (who is in the care of a family member on his fathers side) and an 8 month old son named Jace. Jace lives with us and is the cutest! Emaya loves listening to music on her AirPods, shopping, and being pampered (getting her nails and hair done).

Ella is 4 and the youngest McLeod Fam member. She was 4 months old when she was placed with in our home and 14 months old when I legally adopted her. Ella has been diagnosed with speech delays, pectus excavatum, and limb deficiencies. Ella loves spinning, playing with her dolls, and watching Finding Nemo!

Together we are The McLeod Fam! Thank you to all those who have loved & supported us 🌈

Good vibrations ☀️😎

Today was one of those days as a parent that I wanted to get in my car, drive somewhere far far away, and never come back 🤣 Being a single mom is NOT easy. Don’t let the videos and pics fool ya! There are days I want to completely fall apart, but don’t have the luxury of doing that because I have all these tiny (and not so tiny) humans relying on me.

But today I refused to let the stress bring me down. I told Mya let’s get the kids ready and get the hell out of this house! Best decision I’ve made in a longggg time 😃 Eli wore a mask for the FIRST time with ZERO kickback and ALL these wild animals (aka my kids and grandson) actually behaved themselves in public 😮 I am not kidding you when I say that’s literally never happened 😆 Mya stopped at @sephora for a fun makeover while the kids and I enjoyed dinner. And we nailed 2 major milestones…Jace and Emaya’s first time at the beach 🏖 Today was a really, really good day 🤗

I can hardly believe Ella is going to be 4 in just about a week! Where does the time go?! This photo was taken in line for Small World on Ella’s first trip to Disneyland. She was about 9 months old 👶🏼 I know many of you ask why Ella isn’t featured on our page as much. As I have stated repeatedly, Ella is young. Evan actively asks (more like demands) to be photographed and in videos. Ella is little and as a parent I’m giving her the space to BE little 🎀

That being said, I’m so glad so many of you have fallen in love with the youngest member of The McLeod Fam 💗 Ella is a determined little soul and has recently begun exhibiting certain behaviors that lead me to believe she may be autistic. Her first neurology appointment is in a few weeks and I have no doubt that her doctor will provide anything less than the very best of care 🩺

And YES, Evan and Ella are biological siblings. I get asked that question a lot. I made the decision to accept one more placement because I wanted Evan and Ella to have one another for life. To be able to grow up together and lean on one another. I’ve said it before and I’ll say it again, they’re the BEST gifts I could have ever given the other 💞

I gotta order a cake for this little Disney Princess today so we can celebrate her birthday in style! Can any of you guess who her favorite princess is???

node.text:
Foster child.
Teen mom.
8th grade education.
Runaway.
Extensive trauma history.
Domestic violence victim.
Assault record.
Difficult placement.

This was my daughter on paper. The words a social worker first spoke to me shortly followed by “If you don’t take her, no one will.” It’s incredible and heartbreaking how an individual can be so easily pieced apart and labeled. She was words on a piece of paper. Another number. A statistic to add to all the foster care studies.

Now replace those words with:

Loving.
Funny.
Beautiful (inside & out).
Good mother.
Intelligent.
Amazing cook.
Strong. So strong.
Resilient.
An absolute force to be reckoned with.

Her pictures don’t do her justice. Emaya has overcome obstacles in her life most of us wouldn’t survive. She continues to face ongoing adversity, judgment, and discrimination. All because of a past she had little to no control over. But she’s fighting her way forward and I’m humbled to be apart of her incredible journey 🥺 Her dream is to become a model and judging by her photos I’d have to say her “big break” is definitely on the horizon. And she will have earned and rightfully deserve every opportunity and accolade that comes her way.

Emaya says it best when she says she is healing from her past. And I am so so so proud of the woman she IS and the woman she will become.

node.text:
“Your face isn’t ‘likeable’.”

I remember someone telling me this as a pre-teen. The standard of beauty during the late 80’s and 90’s was blonde hair, blue eyes, slim noses, etc. I was anything and everything completely opposite of that. I have a wide nose, big lips, and giant eyes. My face has always been very round even when I was at my thinnest.

If I’m being honest, much of my life I’ve hated my face. My own mother once told me I was an ugly duckling (to which she added that I grew into my looks…that did not make that statement better 😂). It took me a long time to embrace my biracial features. The features that once made my face unlikable to others are what make me ME!

It’s taken me years to embrace who I am inside and out. To love the things about me that others criticized, critiqued, and belittled. From pain comes beauty and I have more than learned to embrace the beauty that is my own diversity. I’m queer, I’m here, and I’m breathtaking.
